---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="The Banlist">
  <main class="design-essay">
    
    <header class="essay-header">
      <span class="super-title">Design Philosophy VI</span>
      <h1>The Banlist</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Identity via Exclusion</p>
    </header>

    <hr />

    <article class="prose-block">
      <p class="lead-paragraph">
        In TLR, not all bans serve the same role. Some define what TLR is allowed 
        to be. Others exist to protect how games feel and play. Understanding 
        that difference is important for discussing future changes, and setting 
        clear expectations for the format.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>At its core, this philosophy isn’t only about what TLR allows, but rather it’s about clearly communicating what TLR is not.</strong>
      </p>
    </article>

    <section class="chapter-section">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>TLR Is Intentionally Below Vintage Power</h3>
        <p>
          TLR pulls from an Eternal card pool, but it is not built to support Vintage-level efficiency. 
          The format is designed with a much lower baseline for mana, card draw, and resource conversion.
        </p>
        <p>
          Many Vintage-legal cards rely on assumptions that simply don’t hold in TLR, such as:
        </p>
        <ul class="standard-list">
          <li>Games being defined in the first one or two turns by explosive mana</li>
          <li>Zero- or one-mana card advantage at extreme rates</li>
          <li>A metagame shaped around free or near-free interaction</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          TLR does not adopt those assumptions. As a result, some cards that are legal in Vintage are 
          incompatible with TLR by default. These cards aren’t banned because of specific combos or 
          dominant archetypes, they’re banned because their mere presence pushes the format toward 
          a Vintage-adjacent experience.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section alt-bg">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>Defining the Format’s Power Ceiling</h3>
        <p>
          Some bans exist to clearly establish how powerful TLR is willing to be. These aren’t metagame 
          fixes or temporary safety valves. These bans define the upper bounds of the format.
        </p>
        <p>
          Cards in this space tend to be at a rate that is so efficient, the rest of the format has to 
          bend around them. Allowing them would force changes to deck construction, interaction density, 
          and overall gameplay expectations.
        </p>
        
        <h4>Vintage-Rate Power</h4>
        <p>These cards are banned to reinforce that TLR is not balanced around Vintage-era efficiency:</p>
        
        <div class="card-grid">
          <span>Ancestral Recall</span>
          <span>Balance</span>
          <span>Channel</span>
          <span>Fastbond</span>
          <span>Library of Alexandria</span>
          <span>Necropotence</span>
          <span>Skullclamp</span>
          <span>Strip Mine</span>
          <span>Time Vault</span>
          <span>Time Walk</span>
          <span>Timetwister</span>
          <span>Wheel of Fortune</span>
          <span>Yawgmoth’s Will</span>
        </div>

        <p class="footnote">
          Being listed here doesn’t mean these cards are “forever impossible” to revisit, but unbanning 
          them would require extensive testing, intentional environmental support, and a format ecosystem 
          built to absorb their impact without collapsing into Vintage-style play.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>Permanent Fast Mana</h3>
        <p>
          TLR already plays quickly due to its core rule structure, particularly the Rule of 3, which 
          compresses curves across the format. Because the baseline speed is high, permanent fast mana 
          has an outsized effect.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rather than simply enabling strong starts, these cards turn opening hands into deterministic 
          lines, flatten meaningful resource development, and shrink early interaction windows.
        </p>

        <div class="card-grid three-col">
          <span data-set="leb">Black Lotus</span>
          <span data-set="">Chrome Mox</span>
          <span>Gaea’s Cradle</span>
          <span>Jeweled Lotus</span>
          <span data-set="mir">Lion’s Eye Diamond</span>
          <span>Mana Crypt</span>
          <span>Mana Vault</span>
          <span>Mishra’s Workshop</span>
          <span>Mox Amber</span>
          <span>Mox Diamond</span>
          <span>Mox Emerald</span>
          <span>Mox Jet</span>
          <span>Mox Opal</span>
          <span>Mox Ruby</span>
          <span>Mox Sapphire</span>
          <span>Sol Ring</span>
          <span>Tolarian Academy</span>
        </div>

        <p>
          These cards aren’t completely judged in isolation, they're evaluated based on how they interact 
          with TLR’s already-compressed cost structure. This category is also not a blanket rejection 
          of future mana acceleration. Conditional or restrictive fast mana is evaluated on a case-by-case 
          basis.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>Tutors & Singleton Pressure</h3>
        <p>
          Singleton is a core pillar of TLR’s identity. Low-cost, unconditional tutors work directly 
          against that goal by reducing variance and turning decks into consistent toolboxes.
        </p>
        
        <div class="card-grid">
          <span>Demonic Tutor</span>
          <span>Imperial Seal</span>
          <span>Mystical Tutor</span>
          <span>Survival of the Fittest</span>
          <span>Vampiric Tutor</span>
        </div>
        
        <p>
          These bans exist to preserve uncertainty, distinct deck identities, and meaningful decisions 
          under imperfect information.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section alt-bg">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>Bans Focused on Play Experience</h3>
        <p>
          Some cards aren’t banned to define power level, but to protect the quality of games. Because 
          of TLR’s deck size, compact spectrum of mana values, or Commander-variant structure, these 
          cards become disproportionately strong or disruptive.
        </p>

        <div class="ban-reason-list">
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Counterbalance</span>
            <span class="reason">With only four mana values (0–3), it becomes excessively consistent.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Karakas</span>
            <span class="reason">Almost antithetical to the spirit of playing with a commander and almost always has a valid target.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Lutri, the Spellchaser</span>
            <span class="reason">Singleton nature of the format does not meaningfully restrict it.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Price of Progress</span>
            <span class="reason">Nonbasic-heavy singleton manabases turn this into a near-guaranteed finisher.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Tasha’s Hideous Laughter</span>
            <span class="reason">Small decks and low mana values push it far beyond intent.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h4>Designed for Multiplayer</h4>
        <p>
          Some cards are balanced around multiplayer politics and pressure. In 1v1 TLR, those safeguards 
          disappear, allowing advantages to snowball uncontested.
        </p>
        <div class="card-grid">
          <span>Court of Cunning</span>
          <span>Forth Eorlingas!</span>
          <span>Maddening Hex</span>
          <span>White Plume Adventurer</span>
        </div>

        <h4>Physical Dexterity & Logistics</h4>
        <div class="card-grid">
          <span>Chaos Orb</span>
          <span>Falling Star</span>
          <span>Shahrazad</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>Format-Level Eligibility Exclusions</h3>
        <p>Some exclusions have nothing to do with power or balance.</p>
        <ul class="standard-list">
          <li><strong>Non-Standard Frames/Stamps:</strong> Silver-bordered, gold-bordered, and Acorn-stamped cards.</li>
          <li><strong>Conspiracy Cards:</strong> They bypass in-game decision-making.</li>
          <li><strong>Offensive Content:</strong> Cards with racially or culturally offensive presentation.</li>
          <li><strong>Ante Cards:</strong> Real-world stakes are not supported.</li>
          <li><strong>Stickers and Attractions:</strong> Added logistics burden.</li>
          <li><strong>Digital-Only Cards:</strong> TLR is a paper-only format.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>Banned as Tiny Leader (Commander)</h3>
        <p>
          TLR uses a command zone. That changes how some cards function. Guaranteed access introduces 
          inevitability and repeatability that doesn’t exist when cards must be drawn naturally.
        </p>
        <p>
          Cards banned as a Tiny Leader often generate overwhelming advantages, deny resources in ways 
          that create non-games, or bypass normal risk.
        </p>

        <div class="ban-reason-list detailed">
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Ajani, Nacatl Pariah</span>
            <span class="reason">A low mana investment that quickly snowballs into repeatable pressure, removal, and damage.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Ashiok, Dream Render</span>
            <span class="reason">Honestly, I don’t know. Somebody help here.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Derevi, Imperial Tactician</span>
            <span class="reason">Circumvents commander tax, creating persistent mana/tempo advantages and resource denial.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Erayo, Soratami Ascendant</span>
            <span class="reason">Command‑zone access dramatically lowers the setup cost for establishing a near‑lock state.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Jeska, Thrice Reborn</span>
            <span class="reason">Enables disproportionate burst damage that scales over the game with minimal board commitment.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Ketramose, the New Dawn</span>
            <span class="reason">Powerful card draw allows early advantage and rapid recovery, overwhelming normal pacing.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Nadu, Winged Wisdom</span>
            <span class="reason">Enables explosive value chains of card draw and mana acceleration, compressing interaction windows.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Rofellos, Llanowar Emissary</span>
            <span class="reason">Provides extreme mana acceleration by default, invalidating normal development curves.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Uro, Titan of Nature’s Wrath</span>
            <span class="reason">Repeated access to ramp, card draw, and life gain creates inevitability with minimal disruption.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ban-item">
            <span class="card-name">Wrenn and Six</span>
            <span class="reason">Recursive fetchland access improves consistency; repeated land destruction (Wasteland) can lock opponents out.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="footnote">
          These cards are generally fine in the 49, where variance and risk are reestablished. In the 
          command zone, they centralize games around a single known effect in ways that run counter to 
          TLR’s goals.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <footer class="essay-footer prose-block">
      <h3>Closing Thoughts</h3>
      <p>
        TLR’s banlist is intentional & reactive, but not reactionary. Some bans define the ceiling. 
        Others protect how games feel beneath it. Together, they keep the format recognizable, 
        deliberate, and distinct.
      </p>
    </footer>

    <nav class="series-nav">
      
      <a href="/design/sideboard" class="nav-card prev">
        <span class="nav-label">Previous</span>
        <div class="nav-inner">
          <span class="nav-arrow">&larr;</span>
          <span class="chapter-title">Sideboard - 10 Cards</span>
        </div>
      </a>

      <a href="/design/modular-system" class="nav-card next">
        <span class="nav-label">Next Element</span>
        <div class="nav-inner">
          <span class="chapter-title">Modular System</span>
          <span class="nav-arrow">&rarr;</span>
        </div>
      </a>

    </nav>

  </main>

    <div id="card-tooltip" class="hidden">
        <img id="tooltip-img" src="" alt="Card Preview" />
    </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* --- REUSING DESIGN SYSTEM STYLES --- */
  .design-essay {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 3rem 1rem;
    color: var(--text-body);
  }

  .prose-block {
    max-width: 65ch;
    margin: 0 auto;
    line-height: 1.8;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
  }

  /* --- HEADER --- */
  .essay-header { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 3rem; }
  .super-title { font-size: 0.85rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--accent); font-weight: bold; display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .essay-header h1 { font-size: 3rem; color: var(--heading-color); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.1; }
  .subtitle { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-muted); font-style: italic; }
  .lead-paragraph { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--heading-color); }

  /* --- SECTIONS --- */
  .chapter-section { padding: 3rem 0; }
  .chapter-section h3 { font-size: 1.75rem; color: var(--heading-color); margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .chapter-section h4 { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--accent); margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }

  /* --- CARD GRIDS --- */
  .card-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(180px, 1fr));
    gap: 0.5rem 1.5rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  .three-col {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(140px, 1fr));
  }

  .card-grid span {
    /* Change to a Serif stack that looks like parchment/fantasy */
    font-family: "Goudy Old Style", "Garamond", "Georgia", serif; 
    
    /* Make it bold to look like the Title Bar of a card */
    font-weight: 700; 
    
    /* Slight spacing helps mimic the Beleren font */
    letter-spacing: 0.03em; 
    
    font-size: 1.05rem; /* Bumped up slightly since serifs read smaller */
    color: var(--heading-color);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    padding: 0.25rem 0;
  }

  /* --- BAN REASON LIST --- */
  .ban-reason-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .ban-item {
    background-color: var(--bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 1rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }

  .card-name {
    display: block;
    
    /* The Magic Card Title Font Stack */
    font-family: "Goudy Old Style", "Garamond", "Georgia", serif;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.03em;

    color: var(--heading-color);
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
    font-size: 1.15rem; /* Slight bump for readability */
  }

  .reason {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--text-body);
  }

  /* --- LISTS --- */
  .standard-list {
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }
  .standard-list li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

  .footnote {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }

  /* --- ALT BACKGROUND --- */
  .alt-bg {
    background-color: var(--surface);
    margin-left: calc(-50vw + 50%);
    margin-right: calc(-50vw + 50%);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    padding-right: 1rem;
    width: 100vw;
  }

  /* --- NAVIGATION --- */
  .series-nav {
    margin-top: 6rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: flex-end;
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  .nav-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    text-decoration: none;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 300px;
    padding: 1rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 1px solid transparent;
    transition: all 0.2s ease;
  }

  .nav-card:hover {
    background-color: var(--surface);
    border-color: var(--border-subtle);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .nav-inner { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; }
  .prev { align-items: flex-start; text-align: left; }
  .next { align-items: flex-end; text-align: right; }
  .nav-label { font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: bold; }
  .chapter-title { font-size: 1rem; font-weight: bold; color: var(--heading-color); }
  .nav-arrow { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--accent); }

  /* --- SCRYFALL TOOLTIP --- */
  #card-tooltip {
    position: fixed; /* Fixed relative to viewport so it follows mouse easily */
    z-index: 1000;   /* On top of everything */
    pointer-events: none; /* Let mouse clicks pass through it */
    
    width: 240px;    /* Standard MTG card width on screen */
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 10px; /* Rounded corners like a card */
    box-shadow: 0 10px 25px rgba(0,0,0,0.5); /* Deep shadow for float effect */
    background-color: #000; /* Background while loading */
    
    transition: opacity 0.2s ease;
  }

  #tooltip-img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
    border-radius: 10px;
  }

  /* Utility to hide it */
  #card-tooltip.hidden {
    opacity: 0;
    visibility: hidden;
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .alt-bg { margin-left: -1rem; margin-right: -1rem; width: calc(100% + 2rem); }
    .series-nav { flex-direction: column; gap: 2rem; }
    .nav-card { max-width: 100%; align-items: center; text-align: center; background-color: var(--surface); border-color: var(--border-subtle); }
    .prev, .next { align-items: center; text-align: center; }
  }
</style>

<script>
  // 1. Select all card elements (both grid items and detailed list items)
  const cardElements = document.querySelectorAll('.card-grid span, .card-name');
  const tooltip = document.getElementById('card-tooltip');
  const tooltipImg = document.getElementById('tooltip-img');

  cardElements.forEach(el => {
    // 2. Mouse Enter: Fetch image and show tooltip
    el.addEventListener('mouseenter', (e) => {
      const cardName = el.textContent.trim();
      const setCode = el.getAttribute('data-set'); // Check for specific set version

      // Base Scryfall URL
      let imageUrl = `https://api.scryfall.com/cards/named?exact=${encodeURIComponent(cardName)}&format=image&version=normal`;
      
      // If a set code exists, append it to the URL
      if (setCode) {
        imageUrl += `&set=${setCode}`;
      }
      
      // Set the source
      tooltipImg.src = imageUrl;
      
      // Remove hidden class
      tooltip.classList.remove('hidden');
    });

    // 3. Mouse Move: Follow the cursor
    el.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
      // Offset slightly so cursor doesn't cover the card
      const xOffset = 20;
      const yOffset = 20;

      // Check if card would go off right side of screen
      // If so, flip it to the left of the cursor
      if (e.clientX + 260 > window.innerWidth) { // 260 is approx tooltip width
         tooltip.style.left = (e.clientX - 260) + 'px';
      } else {
         tooltip.style.left = (e.clientX + xOffset) + 'px';
      }

      tooltip.style.top = (e.clientY + yOffset) + 'px';
    });

    // 4. Mouse Leave: Hide tooltip
    el.addEventListener('mouseleave', () => {
      tooltip.classList.add('hidden');
      tooltipImg.src = ''; // Clear src to prevent flashing old card next time
    });
  });
</script>